<br>
I was wasps in Burning Woods.  For the lower level wasps, I would pull with my Burnt Wood Staff, {I have a horse an it was more medding time while waiting for staff to go off}, send in the pet, and then nuke with Swords of Swords.  The Cinderbolt from the Burnt Wood staff was partially resisted a lot and fully resisted, but did not really matter because is was medding time and the pet was not getting beat on.  <br>
<br>
After I found out that I could cast the item immediately, I would pull with the Burnt Wood Staff, send in pet, start casting Shock of swords, and then alternate Burnt Wood Staff and Shock of swords with no delay.  I noticed that the Burnt Wood Staff hit for 333 every time.  {Pretty darn good for highly fire resistant wasps}  <br>
<br>
Yesterday, against light blues, I only used the Burnt Wood Staff and noticed that I was being resisted a lot.  <br>
<br>
My theory is this.  <br>
When you start casting a spell, all the relevant spell information is put into the &quot;active spell database&quot;. IE, focus effects, Max Damage, Casting Time, resists, etc.  At the time the spell hits the mob, it checks this database to calculate the effects.  For DD spells, they hit immediately and the database is correct.  For bolt spells, most of the time they hit before you can start casting again and often will use the same spell again so the database is correct.  But look what happens if you alternate the Burnt wood staff with a shock of swords immediately.  The &quot;active spell database&quot; has information for Shock of Swords and not Cinderbolt.  They no longer have the info for the Cinderbolt and instead just use the default damage.  <br>
<br>
This fits with what I have observed using my Burnt Wood Staff/Shock of Blades against Wasps in Burnt Woods. {May not be right however.}  <br>
<br>
Gee, I wonder if you can hurt extremely high MR/FR resistant mobs this way??<br>
<br>
